## 4.4 Spatio-Temporal Transferability

### 4.4.1 Spatial Transferability

The spatial transferability of the VegHealthCNN model was assessed through two complementary approaches. First, the Spatial Block Cross-Validation framework (Section 4.2) provided a quantitative measure of spatial generalization: the model achieved 96% accuracy on test blocks that were geographically separated from the training blocks by a minimum distance determined by the 0.01° grid structure. This result confirms that the learned spectral features are not spatially specific to the training sub-region.

Second, the model was trained exclusively on ground-truth samples from the AKAA sub-region and subsequently applied to the full extent of the Prestea Huni-Valley Municipality—a substantially larger area encompassing diverse land-cover types, topographic conditions, and agricultural practices not represented in the training data. The resulting classification map (Figure 4.4) exhibits spatial coherence and agronomic plausibility, with healthy vegetation dominant in forested areas and agricultural lands, moderate stress concentrated near degraded zones, and non-vegetation correctly delineated in urban and mining areas.

### 4.4.2 Temporal Transferability

